abstract: AMSTERDAM, N.Y., May 1. -- This evening while the Forty-sixth Separate Company was making preparations to leave for Hempstead to-morrow, George De Graff was shot and killed by a revolver in the hands of a companion named Wilbur Jeralmon. Jeralmon pointed the revolver at De Graff, thinking the weapon was not loaded, when it was discharged, and the bullet entered the mouth of De Graff and passed through his head.

abstract: NORFOLK, Va., May 2. -- The gunboat Bancroft arrived at the Norfolk Navy Yard to-day. Some repairs will be made on the little vessel. abstract: SANTA CRUZ, Cal., May 4. -- There is no evidence to indicate that the recent explosion in the powder mills here was caused by Spanish spies. The output is now 5,000 pounds of smokeless and 1,200 pounds of brown powder daily. abstract: FORT LEE, N.J., May 4. -- There was a serious accident on the Leonia Hill this afternoon. Rev. abstract: CHICAGO, May 7. -- May wheat advanced to $1.70 per bushel on the Board of Trade to-day. It closed yesterday worth $1.49 3/4. July added 5 3/8 cents to its value. abstract: According to De Quincey, the supreme prize in life is the union of a fine intellect and a healthy stomach. Why this combination of blessings is so rare is easy to see. The brain is selfish, and the more active it is, the more blood it takes from the stomach. That the stomach may need the blood for the digestion of a tough, intractable dinner makes no difference to the brain.

abstract: One of the latest events in meteorites was the explosion and fall of stones which occurred at Madrid on 10th February, 1896. This happened on a fine morning, and the explosion seemed to come from a rapidly-moving cloudlet in the blue sky. The description is probably correct, for it agrees with what is taken as the accepted theory with regard to these visitors from the heavens.

abstract: ONE of the largest altars in the country was consecrated last Sunday at the Church of St. Joachim, Mount Loretto, S. I. It is a beautiful piece of work, 35 feet in height. abstract: RED BANK, N.J., May 23. -- The Red Bank and Long Branch trolley road passed into the hands of James E. Degnan, as receiver, to-day. The road has been losing money since its inception. abstract: Apart from all concomitant danger of blood poisoning, the severity of the bites of flesh-eating animals is out of all proportion to the weapons by which they are inflicted. The teeth, even of the largest carnivora, are merely the "spearhead"; but the force which "works" these instruments is prodigious. It seems as if for the moment the animal threw all its bodily energy into the combination of muscular action which we call a "bite."

abstract: Flogging by the knout has been prohibited in Siberia. It is allowed only on this island of Sakhalin, and for murder. No Russian civilian is allowed to witness an execution of that sort; certainly no traveler. You can look over any book you like, even any romance you like, and I think you will find that no author ventures to say that he himself saw a case of flogging.
